<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Channel 4 attacks ITV sales effort
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHAIRMAN of Channel 4 yesterday attacked the ITV companies for
apparently underselling Channel 4 advertising in the past three years.
The period coincides with the passage of the 1990 Broadcasting Act, when it
became clear Channel 4 would be selling advertising-time in competition with
ITV. Sir Michael Bishop, Channel 4 chairman, said: 'It is remarkable that
from 1989, while our audience share continued to grow, ITV suddenly seemed
to have difficulty in selling our advertising effectively.'
In 1992, when Channel 4 had 19.9 per cent of the non-satellite commercial
audience, ITV attributed 14 per cent of its advertising income to Channel 4,
Sir Michael said. This 'by some strange coincidence' matched the 14 per cent
revenue safety net.
Mr Michael Grade , the Channel 4 chief executive, declined to comment on an
industry belief that Channel 4 was taking about 17 per cent of total
advertising.
Channel 4 also confirmed that the BBC paid it Pounds 65,000 after the
departure of Ms Liz Forgan, its former programme director, to be managing
director of BBC Radio. The money repaid a 'golden handcuff' paid to Ms
Forgan.
</TEXT>
