<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Germany's plan on deportation runs into snag
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY'S plan to deport asylum-seekers to neighbouring countries, approved
in parliament on Wednesday, could be held up by Czech officials unwilling to
take them back.
Mr Josef Zileniec, the Czech foreign affairs minister said yesterday Germany
should understand it could not solve its domestic security issues at the
cost of the Czech republic.
Czech officials have indicated they will only agree to take back
asylum-seekers from Germany once proper border controls are set up with
Slovakia.
The bulk of asylum-seekers coming from the former Yugoslavia, Romania and
Bulgaria cross the former Czechoslovak territory.
'We first need assurances that countries such as Romania and Bulgaria will
take them back,' an official at the Czech foreign affairs ministry said. 'We
also need a proper border with Slovakia. This could take two years to be set
up,' he added.
German conservative MPs on Wednesday hailed a deportation agreement signed
three weeks ago with Poland. Under the agreement, Poland will take back
10,000 asylum-seekers this year and an unlimited amount thereafter. Germany
is offering DM120m (Pounds 47.8m) to build the infrastructure to host the
asylum-seekers.
The agreement with Poland was a crucial weapon in winning over the
opposition Social Democrats who opposed for a long time the constitutional
change.
The new law dilutes the automatic right of a person to seek asylum upon
entering Germany. Instead, guards will be able to turn back at the border
asylum-seekers 'with manifestedly unfounded' claims to 'safe' countries.
Officials at the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees in Bonn have
warned that the German constitutional change will only partly curb the
influx of foreigners into Germany. A high number are expected to enter the
country illegally, now that filing an asylum demand no longer ensures they
can legally stay in the country for a period of time.
Plans to reinforce surveillance on Germany's eastern borders are under way,
with an additional 1,700 police men due to take up duty later this summer.
The interior ministry is also testing infra-red equipment which will allow
border trespassers to be seen at night.
According to the interior ministry, tougher security measures are also
planned for Frankfurt airport, where border guards will be able to send back
asylum-seekers coming from countries where no violations of human rights
have been reported.
</TEXT>
