<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / US cuts Dollars 30m in aid to Guatemala
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Agencies
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US cut off more than Dollars 30m (Pounds 19.40m) in assistance to
Guatemala yesterday because of the suspension of democracy there, agencies
report.
The decision came as the military in Guatemala City sent armoured cars and
troops to break up a demonstration, which reflected mounting opposition to
President Jorge Serrano's seizure of near-dictatorial powers.
Despite a ban on demonstrations, an estimated 1,000 protesters gathered in
the city outside the Supreme Court where nine new members, hand-picked by Mr
Serrano, were to be sworn in.
The US State Department again appealed to Mr Serrano to reverse his actions
and suspended cash transfers to the Guatemalan government and military and
police training programmes. The aid cuts also apply to development
assistance and food aid channeled through the government. Aid channeled
through private groups, including humanitarian assistance, can continue.
Yesterday's announcement did not provide a figure on the value of the
suspended aid but officials said it was in excess of Dollars 30m. Dollars
45m in food aid and development assistance had been planned for Guatemala in
fiscal 1993. Also planned were Dollars 2.5m in anti-narcotics aid and
Dollars 400,000 for military training.
On Tuesday Mr Serrano dissolved the Congress and the judiciary and said he
planned to rule by decree until a new constitution was drafted. The US said
the suspension of the constitution put Guatemala 'on a dangerous course'.
</TEXT>
