FT  28 MAY 93 / Czechs warn Germany on tighter asylum laws
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GERMANY'S plan to curb the influx of asylum-seekers, approved in the
Bundestag on Wednesday, could be hampered by Czech unwillingness to take
back deportees.
Mr Josef Zileniec, the Czech foreign affairs minister, said yesterday
Germany should understand it could not solve its domestic security issues at
the cost of the Czech republic.
Most asylum-seekers from the former Yugoslavia, Romania and Bulgaria cross
the former Czechoslovak territory on their way to Germany.
Czech officials have indicated they want certain assurances before agreeing
to allow back such asylum-seekers barred by Germany.
'We first need assurances that countries such as Romania and Bulgaria will
take them back,' a Czech official said. 'We also need a proper border with
Slovakia. This could take two years to be set up.'
German conservative MPs have welcomed a deportation agreement signed three
weeks ago with Poland. Under the agreement, Poland will take back 10,000
asylum-seekers this year and an unlimited number thereafter. Germany is
offering DM120m (Pounds 47.8m) to build the infrastructure to host the
asylum-seekers.
The agreement with Poland was crucial to winning over the opposition Social
Democrats, who for a long time opposed changing Germany's constitution to
dilute its guarantee of political asylum to foreigners.
In future, border guards will be able to stop asylum-seekers 'with
manifestedly unfounded' claims, turning them back to 'safe' countries.
But it is feared more foreigners will try to enter Germany illegally.
Surveillance on Germany's eastern borders will be stepped up, with 1,700
more police taking up duty later this summer. Officials are also testing
infra-red equipment that will allow border trespassers to be seen at night.
