<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow hits new high as hopes
rise for package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
BLUE CHIP stocks climbed to new heights yesterday as hopes rose that
President Bill Clinton's tax-raising deficit-reduction package would be
approved by the House of Representatives, writes Patrick Harverson in New
York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 14.67 higher at 3,554.83, another
record close. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500, however, ended 1.03 off at 452.41.
The American SE composite gained 1.80 at 438.93 and the Nasdaq composite was
up 0.50 at 704.59. New York SE volume came to 301m shares.
The markets picked up where they had left off on Wednesday, when heavy late
buying lifted the Dow to its second record finish in a week. Analysts had
anticipated fresh early gains, primarily because stocks traditionally do
well in the days leading up to a long weekend. On Monday the markets will be
shut for the Memorial Day holiday.
Attention was firmly focused on Capitol Hill, where the House was due to
vote on the Clinton economic package last night. Although investors are not
particularly keen on Mr Clinton's plan to raise taxes, they fear that a
defeat in the House would be a severe setback for his presidency. Moreover,
the markets, especially the bond market, are generally supportive of the
package as it appears to be the first meaningful attempt by a US government
to reduce the huge budget deficit.
Chevron jumped Dollars 3 3/4 to Dollars 88 5/8 on news that the oil group
planned to reduce the size of its businesses through a restructuring
programme which will include the sale of some refineries and cutbacks in
retail fuel sales operations. The restructuring will require a Dollars 550m
second quarter charge.
Morgan Stanley climbed Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars 66 after the securities
house unveiled a 40 per cent improvement in first-quarter profits, and
announced that it had found a buyer for Sweetheart, the disposable food
service product manufacturer. The deal will allow Morgan Stanley to
eliminate its costly bridge loan to Sweetheart.
Student Loan Marketing, which has been hit recently by speculation
surrounding the administration's plans to shake up financing for students in
higher education, fell Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 45 in busy trading after
broking house Smith Barney lowered its rating on the stock.
Canada
TORONTO again displayed a firmer tendency after a substantial day's
business. The TSE 300 index ended 4.5 up at 3,869.7 and rises led declines
by 415 to 298 after volume of 67.9m shares. Golds rose 2.3 per cent as the
New York spot gold price gained USDollars 5.75 an ounce.
Northern Telecom tumbled CDollars 1 1/4 to CDollars 45 3/4 on rumours that
Goldman Sachs had downgraded the company.
Seagram slipped CDollars  7/8 to CDollars 37 1/8 in brisk trade after the
Dominion Bond Rating Service said it was placing the firm's debentures and
commercial paper under review and Moody's said it may cut ratings on its
senior debt. Earlier this week Seagram bought 2.1m Time Warner shares.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    CAZ  Canada.
</CN>
