<DATE>930528
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COPPER prices ended easier on the LME after a session of wide price
movements, pulling other metals lower as well. Dealers said copper's
weakness was prompted by recent successive failures above Dollars 1,850 a
tonne for three-month metal, and the market broke downwards below Dollars
1,820, with liquidation, sell stops, and option sales driving prices down to
Dollars 1,795 at one stage. On the London bullion market GOLD remained
locked within the now well established range between Dollars 372 and Dollars
380 a troy ounce. 'There are (sell and buy) stops building up on either side
of this range,' one dealer said, adding that if gold managed to break
through either side, 'we would see a Dollars 5 movement very easily.'
London's robusta COFFEE futures reversed an earlier advance and finished
lower as the recent bout of fund and chart-related buying appeared
temporarily to dry up. New York's arabica coffee was lower across the board
at midday on long liquidation linked to July's early inability to test
10-week highs scored earlier this week. Chicago WHEAT futures were lower at
midday amid light fund selling, which pressed nearby contracts to lifetime
Compiled from Reuters
