<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / International Company News: ConAgra chief to head RJR
Nabisco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RJR NABISCO, the US food and tobacco group, in a surprise move last night
named Mr Charles Harper as chairman and chief executive.
Mr Harper, who is currently chairman of ConAgra and has been credited with
turning that company from a commodities business into a successful packaged
food products group, will take up his new post on Monday.
Only two months ago, RJR Nabisco acted speedily to fill the chairman's post
when Mr Lou Gerstner left to run IBM. RJR set up a 'co-chairman' structure,
splitting the job between Mr Lawrence Ricciardi, formerly its general
counsel, and Mr Karl von der Heyden, finance director.
In March, RJR gave no hint that it would be looking for a new, sole
chairman. Indeed, Mr Ricciardi stressed the arrangement was not an 'interim
step'. Last night, the company said that at that stage, 'frankly there were
no plans to change the structure'. However, it also denied there had been
any disagreements between the co-chairmen.
It said Mr Harper's appointment would help the company 'aggressively pursue
its growth agenda under Mike Harper's leadership as a highly experienced
chief executive with a strong background in consumer products'.
Under the new arrangement, Mr Ricciardi will become president and Mr von der
Heyden will retire.
Mr Harper, 64, retired as chief executive of ConAgra last year, although he
stayed on as chairman, guiding group strategy. He has worked for ConAgra
since 1974.
The appointment of a well-respected executive with long experience of the
food industry comes at a sensitive time for RJR. Its shares have languished,
creating unhappiness among some investors and problems for Kolhbery, Kravis
Roberts, the company's largest shareholder.
</TEXT>
