<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / International Company News: Japanese banks increase loan
provisions by 70%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING Japanese banks yesterday increased their provisions for bad loans by
an average 70 per cent for the year ended March, but made it clear that it
will take them several years to clear away the financial debris from the
lending excesses of the late 1980s.
For the first time, the 11 leading commercial banks, known as city banks in
Japan, announced non-performing loan estimates, ranging from 1.58 per cent
of outstanding loans at Mitsubishi Bank to 4.8 per cent at Hokkaido
Takushoku Bank, and that they have a collective Y8,435.1bn (Dollars 77.67bn)
in problem loans.
However, the amounts do not reflect all the damage done by the domestic
property market collapse, while a 478 per cent year-on-year increase in
write-offs indicates more the low level of previous write-offs than a push
to fully account for problem lending.
Pre-tax profits fell by an average 32.4 per cent, the fourth year of
decline, although a fall in interest rates, a widening of lending spreads,
and a revived bond market enabled the 11 banks to record an average 30.9 per
cent increase in business profits.
The banks' reluctance to write off their bad debts is likely to be matched
by a hesitance to lend in the next few years, meaning that international
companies will face more difficulty in securing Japanese funds and that the
recovery of the domestic economy could be hindered.
Sumitomo Bank, entangled in the collapse of the trading house Itoman, was
the most aggressive in providing for non-performing loans, writing off
Y104.3bn and providing Y97.8bn in fresh reserves, behind an 87.2 per cent
plunge in net profit. Sumitomo, usually the most profitable Japanese
institution, fell to tenth on the net earnings ladder.
But all 11 were able to celebrate capital adequacy ratios comfortably above
the 8 per cent threshold as defined by the Bank for International
Settlements. The ratios of capital to assets ranged from 8.96 per cent at
Sakura Bank to 9.61 per cent at the Bank of Tokyo, after most institutions
took on subordinated debt and trim-med assets to bolster ratios.
Apart from increasing their provisions, bank profits were hit by appraisal
losses on securities holdings, which would have been greater but for a surge
in stock prices in the final weeks of the year.
The banks admit that the favourable conditions from falling interest rates
are passing, and with non-performing loans likely to rise, they will have
difficulty in making provisions without pushing net profits to
embarrassingly low levels.
Details, page 28
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Mitsubishi Bank.
    Hokkaido Takushoku Bank.
    Sumitomo Bank.
    Sakura Bank.
    Bank of Tokyo.
</CO>
<XX>
