<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Queens Moat asks banks for extension
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER and ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 65 banks owed Pounds 1bn by Queens Moat Houses, the hotel company
suspended on the stock market last month, were yesterday urged to extend an
interest and repayments standstill until the end of October.
The company was supported by its bank steering committee, chaired by
Barclays and National Westminster, and said the standstill would give Queens
Moat time to arrange and propose a reconstruction to secure its longer term
financing.
Mr Andrew Coppel, appointed as consultant to Queens Moat last month,
described the steering committee's support as 'extremely positive'. He said
the company would be visiting its bankers over the next 10 days and a
decision on whether they would back the standstill could come in the next
few weeks.
A statement from the steering committee last night pointed to 'very positive
progress' in solving some of Queens Moat's problems. However, bankers
expressed concern at a 'considerable reduction' in Queens Moat asset values,
as revealed by a report from accountants Grant Thornton. The accountants
also reported that Queens Moat made 'substantial losses' last year instead
of profits of about Pounds 80m, as the City once expected.
After a four hour meeting with the banks in the City offices of Allen and
Overy, Queens Moat issued a short statement to confirm that Morgan Grenfell
had replaced Charterhouse as its financial adviser and Coopers &amp; Lybrand had
taken over as auditor from Bird Luckin.
Mr Coppel, former finance director of Ratners, is expected to take over as
chief executive if the banks agree to the standstill. Other board changes
are likely. On Wednesday, Mr Martin Marcus and Mr David Hersey, formerly
deputy chairman and finance director, resigned from the company.
Coopers has begun work on a formal audit for last year, which suggests
Queens Moat may seek to lift its suspension in the autumn. 'The board will
address the question of the relisting when the 1992 results are available,'
Mr Coppel said.
Coopers is also reviewing the company's accounting policies, which have been
heavily criticised since Queens Moat's problems became apparent, and blamed
for some of the profits shortfall.
</TEXT>
