<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Sunday trading bill to offer new option
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is expected to confirm today that it has added a fourth,
'middle ground' option to its draft bill on Sunday trading, which is due to
be published in the next few weeks.
The option is supported by some of the UK's largest retailers, including
Marks and Spencer, Burton and Gateway.
Home office minister Mr Peter Lloyd will tell the Commons that the bill will
include proposals from the Retailers for Shops Act Reform group, which wants
to remove Sunday opening curbs for food and convenience shops of less than
3,000 sq ft and for DIY shops and garden centres, with protection for
workers who refuse to work on Sundays. Under the RSAR proposals large shops
would be barred from opening on Sundays but all shops would be allowed to
open for the last four days before Christmas.
The inclusion of the reform group's proposals may exacerbate the rifts
between retailers on Sunday trading. Sainsbury and Tesco have denounced the
RSAR proposals as ignoring the wishes of customers.
The bill was previously expected to offer only three options, including
total deregulation.
</TEXT>
