<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / BBC to sample viewer opinions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC will send out more than 2m questionnaires each year to viewers in a
'rolling referendum' on its polices, programmes and performance.
The unprecedented sampling of the views of licence-payers is part of a move
towards greater openness and accountability at the corporation.
The BBC said the plan to seek the views of 10 per cent of the 20m-plus
licence-paying homes a year would be cost-effective because questionnaires
would be sent with licence-fee reminders.
Publishing its response to the government green paper on its future, the BBC
said panels of viewers would be convened to advise on policy and programme
strategy.
Mr John Birt, the BBC director-general, said yesterday: 'We are not talking
about being enslaved by this process (of seeking viewers' opinions). It is
meant to inform our judgments and make better decisions.'
In its 154-page response to the government the BBC promised enhanced
accountability, including a clear definition of the role of the BBC
governors and the board of management, an improved complaints procedure and
a new commercial policy framework. Mr Birt said 57 meetings with
licence-payers throughout the UK had 'demonstrated substantial support for
and satisfaction with our existing output'. He described the BBC as 'one of
the most successful institutions created in any country in the twentieth
century'.
The BBC says the government should allow it to continue offering all the
services it does now under a new Royal Charter, but provided more
efficiently with greater openness and accountability.
A study by consultants McKinsey of 11 public-service broadcasters around the
world, published with the main BBC response, found that the licence fee was
potentially the most attractive method of funding to meet public-service
objectives.
Independent market research found 63 per cent in favour and only 14 per cent
against the BBC's preferred programme strategy - concentrating on a broad
range of quality programmes.
Only 24 per cent preferred a more narrow public-service option and 42 per
cent opposed the BBC competing with commercial broadcasters.
Sixty four per cent said the BBC licence fee at Pounds 80 a year was very
good or fairly good value for money, and 72 per cent were against reducing
the range or quality of programmes to cut the licence.
Mr Peter Brooke, the National Heritage secretary, said this week that he
hoped to produce a white paper on the future of the BBC 'at the turn of the
year'.
</TEXT>
