<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / CBI forecasts manufacturing-led recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A MANUFACTURING-led rec-overy which will gather strength later this year is
predicted today by the Confederation of British Industry.
The CBI says manufacturers' order books have strengthened considerably
recently, with export orders showing particular growth due to greater
competitiveness caused by the pound's devaluation.
Mr Andrew Sentance, the CBI's economics director, warned that the big recent
weakening in demand among Britain's trading partners in continental Europe -
largely caused by the deepening German recession - remained a threat to a
sustained upturn.
While the CBI is slightly more bullish about recovery, it says consumer and
industry demand remains weak.
In particular, stocks of finished goods in factory warehouses are fairly
high, indicating that any extra sales of manufactured products may take some
time to spark busier production lines.
In its latest quarterly forecast the CBI says gross domestic product will
increase 1.6 per cent this year and 2.6 per cent next year. In its previous
forecast, in March, it said the figures would be 1.4 per cent and 2.4 per
cent.
Manufacturing output is expected to increase by a respectable 3 per cent
this year, helped by the effects of devaluation, higher productivity and
sluggish wage growth.
In its monthly survey of the commercial outlook facing manufacturers, the
CBI found that order books are at their highest levels for three years and
expectations about output more optimistic than at any time since February
1989.
The CBI says, however, that order books are still rated as 'below normal' by
36 per cent of businesses, with 14 per cent saying they are above normal.
Views about output are more positive, with 37 per cent of companies
expecting sales volumes to increase in the next four months, and only 14 per
cent expecting a decline.
Another finding from the monthly survey, conducted among 1,545 companies
between April 27 and May 19, is that three out of four manufacturers expect
their prices to remain unchanged in the next four months, indicating muted
inflationary pressures.
The CBI is fairly optimistic about inflation, reckoning that annual growth
in the retail prices index, excluding mortgage payments, will be below the
Treasury's 4 per cent target until at least the end of 1994.
</TEXT>
