<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / The Cabinet Reshuffle: Local election results sealed fate of
the 'scapegoat'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS an edge of irritation in Mr John Major's voice earlier this week
when, sitting in his study at 10 Downing Street, he was pressed on Mr Norman
Lamont's future as chancellor.
During the rest of his hour-long interview with the FT on Monday the prime
minister was relaxed and affable. But his response to questions about
whether he was about to reshuffle the cabinet was sharp. He had no intention
of giving the media advance notice of changes. But Mr Major knew as he spoke
that Mr Lamont's days at the Treasury were numbered.
Mr Lamont's fate was sealed on the morning of May 7. As the Conservatives
reeled under the impact of defeats in Newbury and in the county council
elections, those in the prime minister's inner circle drew a damning
conclusion. As long as Mr Lamont stayed on as chancellor there was little
prospect of the government recovering its poise.
More significantly for Mr Major, the chancellor had become a personal
liability. With talk of a challenge to the prime minister in the autumn, he
could not afford to allow Mr Lamont to deliver the November Budget.
As party officials conducted an intensive post-mortem on the election
defeats one factor cropped up again and again. The most powerful weapon
deployed by the Liberal Democrats had been a simple slogan: Voting
Conservative is a vote of confidence in Norman Lamont.
The message was reinforced by an outcry from Conservative constituency
associations. Everywhere party chairman Sir Norman Fowler went he was told
that the party judged that the chancellor had become the focal point for
discontent. No-one would trust the government - nor have confidence in its
economic policies - as long as Mr Lamont was still there.
The conclusion conveyed to Mr Major by Sir Norman and by Mr Richard Ryder,
the chief whip, was that Mr Major's own position depended on him sacking the
man who had run his campaign for the party leadership two-and-a-half years
ago. Private soundings revealed that it was a judgment with which virtually
everyone in the cabinet concurred. And although Mr Lamont still had friends
on the back benches, the message was that they would not fight to keep him.
Mr Lamont thought otherwise. He spent the past two weeks fighting for his
political life - telling friends that he must not be made a scapegoat,
urging support from colleagues.
But the tide became unstoppable. A week ago the prime minister decided he
had to go.
Sir Norman was told at the weekend and spent the next few days in a series
of meetings with the prime minister planning the wider changes which would
accompany Mr Lamont's move. It was thought there was a chance that the
former chancellor would accept the indignity of a move to the department of
the environment. But the reshuffle was planned on the basis that he would
refuse.
The angry manner of Mr Lamont's departure yesterday was public testimony to
his belief that Mr Major had betrayed him. The implicit threat was that he
might now seek his revenge. His words from the back benches will be as
eagerly awaited as those of Mr Nigel Lawson and Sir Geoffrey Howe in the
final days of the Thatcher era.
The message from Downing Street yesterday was that Mr Major had decided to
'refresh' his cabinet. It was true as far as it went.
But no one at Westminster doubted that all the changes were built around a
single aim - to put Mr Kenneth Clarke into the Treasury in time to halt the
fall in the government's popularity and to start preparations for November's
unified budget.
The reshuffle was done with political skill. Mr Major demonstrated his
authority by appointing Mr Clarke in spite of the fears on the Tory right
that he remains wedded to the European exchange rate mechanism and, more
generally, to a central role for Britain in the European Community.
The political balance came from Mr Michael Howard's elevation to the Home
Office. An instinctive right winger is now in charge of an issue that
Conservatives regard as second only in importance to the economy - law and
order.
Mr Howard is now the candidate of the right should Mr Major fall under
Westminster's No 11 bus. Mr John Redwood's elevation to the cabinet and the
choice of Mr David Heathcote-Amory for the European job at the foreign
office were designed to reinforce the same point - Mr Major is sensitive to
the political balance in his party.
Mr Major's hope is that the acrimony will fade, that the Tory right will
judge that there is a common interest in uniting around the new chancellor,
that Mr Clarke will start to persuade the electorate that the government
will sustain the economy recovery and that it has restored its grip.
The prime minister may prove correct. But he is aware of the dangers. There
have been broad hints from friends of Mr Lamont that if there were mistakes
made in the approach to sterling's exit from the European exchange rate
mechanism, they were made by the prime minister. In the crude jargon of
Westminster, Mr Lamont knows where the bodies were buried. He might decide
to reveal them.
Mr Major's recovery depends on his new chancellor reaping the rewards of Mr
Lamont's Treasury stewardship.
If the recovery is sustained and inflation remains low, the restless right
of the Tory party may keep their counsel. Mr Lamont may choose discretion
over revenge. Friends believe that his reputation will be best served by
dignified silence.
But as Mr Major's ministers digested the events of yesterday few denied
there were still far too many 'ifs'. The scars left on the Tory party by the
war over Maastricht will not heal quickly.
Mr Major has dangerous and destructive enemies in his own party. He has
appointed to the most powerful job in his government his most likely
successor. What he needs now, above all else, is a run of political luck.
He had no choice but to sack his chancellor. But it offers no guarantee of
escape.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
