<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / The Cabinet Reshuffle: An English patriot takes on Welsh
role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SUCCESSFUL Tory rightwinger, an able and astute politician and, at heart,
a patriotic Englishman, Mr John Redwood's promotion yesterday to the cabinet
was unsurprising. But his appointment as Welsh secretary was, to say the
least, controversial.
Mr Redwood's elevation from local government minister - after just four
years in ministerial office - helps balance left and right in Mr John
Major's cabinet. Yet in the principality it threatens to reverse a decade of
government interventionism quite unlike the Tories' economic management
elsewhere.
Mr David Hunt, the departing Welsh secretary who was born in Wales and whose
Wirral constituency is at least nearby, was proud of his near-Keynesian
attempts at employment creation. His three years in the job were punctuated
almost daily by press notices on jobs created by Welsh Office initiatives.
But Mr Redwood, 41, is Conservative MP for Wokingham, a town linked to Wales
only by the M4 motorway. He is a crusader for populist capitalism, a former
head of the Number 10 policy unit under Mrs Margaret (now Lady) Thatcher,
and a member of the Thatcherite No Turning Back Group.
Mr Dafydd Wigley, MP for Caernarfon and president of Plaid Cymru, said Mr
Redwood's appointment was 'ominous and ill-considered'.
Mr Redwood is not a believer in the paraphernalia of regional economic
development. His relationship with the Welsh Development Agency will be an
early marker of his style of stewardship. He will also preside over
reorganisation of Welsh local government.
Nor is Mr Redwood a natural European. Privately, he has described himself as
an English nationalist.
Last night Mr Redwood admitted he had no Welsh connections but said on BBC
radio: 'I have been a regular visitor to Wales.' He denied Labour protests
that he was a 'hatchet man' brought in to slash public spending in Wales.
Mr Hunt moves to the Department of Employment, where his presentational
skills will be tested as the government faces relentlessly high levels of
unemployment. He will be eager to develop the plethora of government schemes
for the jobless, although as a one-nation Tory he is unlikely to be keen on
the workfare schemes being floated by rightwing Tories.
Mrs Gillian Shephard moves from the employment department to agriculture. To
some at Westminster the step represented a demotion, but with the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade and other trade issues on the political
agenda, her profile will remain high.
Three ministers were sacked by Mr Major after failing to impress government
business managers. Mr Edward Leigh, the Thatcherite junior minister at the
Department of Trade and Industry, Mr Kenneth Carlisle, junior transport
minister, and Mr Robert Jackson, junior minister at the Office of Public
Service and Science.
Among those promoted were Mr William Hague, who was parliamentary private
secretary to Mr Lamont. He becomes a junior social security minister.
Rightwinger Miss Anne Widdecombe switches from the Department of Social
Security to the employment department where she may take responsibility for
womens' issues.
</TEXT>
<XX>
