<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / The Cabinet Reshuffle: Treasury mandarins await new orders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, PETER MARSH and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WERE no tears and even some jokes as Mr Norman Lamont bade farewell
yesterday to his ministerial team and top aides at an impromptu party in his
Treasury office.
As mandarins sipped white wine and nibbled nuts and crisps, the Treasury
geared up for its first meeting today with Mr Kenneth Clarke, the first
chancellor since Lord Howe in 1979 to have had no experience as a Treasury
minister.
Treasury officials, accustomed to providing a barrage of briefing documents
during a change of government, were yesterday waiting to see what their new
chancellor would want before swinging into action.
However, beyond the unlovely Linoleum Palace overlooking Whitehall, some
commentators are already urging Mr Clarke to take a hard look at the
Treasury's techniques for devising economic policy and its relationship with
the outside world.
Professor Patrick Minford of Liverpool University, one of the 'seven wise
men' appointed earlier this year to advise the Treasury, said Mr Clarke
should 'turn the Treasury upside down' in a quest to learn from recent
policy mistakes.
These included the too-loose monetary policy that led to the late-1980s boom
and the 'disastrous' period of membership of the European exchange rate
mechanism.
Mr Warwick Lightfoot, a former Treasury adviser to Mr Lamont and now a Royal
Bank of Scotland economist, said the new chancellor should 'rebuild'
economic policy by immediately pruning the budget deficit and reviewing the
mechanisms for setting interest rates.
A specific item some outsiders want Mr Clarke to examine is the relationship
between the Treasury and the Bank of England in monetary policy. Mr Keith
Skeoch, chief economist at stockbrokers James Capel, said Mr Clarke should
announce he will take more notice of the Bank in setting interest rates, a
move he said would strengthen the government's credibility with financial
markets.
Professor David Currie, head of economic forecasts at London Business
School, and another of the wise men advising the Treasury, warned that the
new Chancellor would have to take 'decisive action' against the budget
deficit, possibly by increasing taxes and cutting spending.
Mr Andrew Britton, director of the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research, also a 'wise man', said he hoped Mr Clarke's would have better
'political skills' than the former chancellor.
Mr Peter Fellner, UK economist at NatWest Capital Markets, was among those
in the City unmoved by yesterday's events. He said: 'I can't see Kenneth
Clarke being any different from Norman Lamont. The chancellor might have
changed but the problems facing the country haven't'
</TEXT>
