<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / The Cabinet Reshuffle: Opinion divided over former
chancellor's City job prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT MIGHT seem that the obvious future for an ex-chancellor, particularly one
with a merchant banking background, would be back in the City. But opinion
was divided yesterday among top headhunters about Mr Norman Lamont's
immediate job prospects.
Mr Lamont's performance at Rothschilds in the 1970s was not generally
considered to have been outstanding and some headhunters are pointing to his
more recently apparent shortcomings in handling pressure.
More importantly, consultants including Mr Nigel Humphreys, managing
director of Tyzack Accord, referred delicately to Mr Lamont's current
'credibility problem' on economic matters.
Mr Humphreys believes the former chancellor should move out of the limelight
and stay away from 'the greenhouse of business', rather than follow in the
footsteps of some of his predecessors.
Lord Barber, for example, when his time as chancellor ended in 1974, became
chairman of Standard Chartered Bank. Lord Lawson, who resigned as chancellor
in 1989, became a director of Barclays Bank and the troubled GPA group. Sir
John Nott, a Treasury minister in the 1970s, became chairman and chief
executive of Lazard Brothers.
Mr Lamont's long-term interests might be best served by going for a top job
in the World Bank or the World Health Organisation, Mr Humphreys said.
Playing an ambassadorial role for a while would be 'a great credibility
builder,' he said. Alternatively, a job away from home, possibly with a
multinational headquartered in continental Europe, could be a possibility.
Such an organisation might consider it a coup 'to hook a foreign chancellor
of the exchequer,' he added.
Mr Paul Buchanan-Barrow, partner with headhunters Korn/Ferry, took the
opposite view of Mr Lamont's prospects. 'I can think of a number of chairmen
who would be self-confident enough to take him on,' he said. That would
include chairmen of banks as well as large corporations. A separate source
named Hambros as a possibility.
Mr Stephen Bampfylde, managing director of headhunters Saxton Bampfylde,
said he 'looked forward to sitting down with Mr Lamont to discuss the
matter'. The former chancellor's range of experience would make him an
'attractive individual for many clients'. Mr Bampfylde said it was no longer
a 'business of selling contacts - that's regarded as vulgar. It's more being
able to say 'this is how Brussels would react', or 'this is how the World
Bank would see things'.'
</TEXT>
