<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Property leasing changes proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEPARTMENT of the Environment yesterday published a consultation paper
on commercial property leases, which could lead to far-reaching changes in
the UK property industry, Vanessa Houlder writes.
The government is seeking responses to a number of possible changes,
including the prohibition of upward-only rent review clauses, the
prohibition of confidentiality clauses and establishment of a body to
arbitrate disputed rent reviews.
Responses to the proposals are sought by September 30.
The decision to issue a consultation paper follows widespread criticism of
commercial leases by tenants. They say that practices such as upward-only
reviews and confidentiality clauses have favoured landlords over tenants and
increased recessionary pressures on their businesses.
Significant government intervention in commercial leases would be opposed by
landlords, however. They believe it could cut property values and deter
development.
The government has said it does not intend legislating in any way to alter
the terms in existing contracts.
</TEXT>
