<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Heseltine undermines travel industry rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW REGULATIONS for the package travel industry were in disarray yesterday
after it emerged that Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary, had told an Oxford-based holiday company it did not have to
protect customers' money because it allowed them to specify what ferry
service they wished to use.
The company, SFV Holidays which went into liquidation last Friday, had taken
800 bookings for French self-catering accommodation this summer. The company
is unbonded.
Mr John Cullom, managing director, said yesterday he hoped to announce early
next week that the company had been sold and that customers' holidays were
safe.
He said SVF had believed that, under a European Community directive, it was
obliged to ensure that travellers' deposits and payments could be returned.
He said Mr Heseltine's view - set out in two letters to Mr John Patten, the
education secretary and MP for Oxford - that the company did not have to
comply 'surprised us enormously'.
Mr Stephen Hickman, acting head of the consumer section of the Oxfordshire
Trading Standards department, said trading standards officers had told the
company that if it sold ferry crossings as well as holidays it had to comply
with the regulations.
Mr Cullom said 95 per cent of its customers bought travel and accommodation.
The EC directive applies if a company provides a pre-arranged combination of
accommodation and transport at an inclusive price. Companies can arrange a
bond through an organisation such as the Association of British Travel
Agents or the Association of Independent Tour Operators, take out an
insurance policy, or hold customer deposits in separate accounts.
SFV's application to join Aito was rejected last October. Aito said
yesterday the company 'did not have the right profile'. It is believed Aito
had come across several complaints about SFV.
SFV wrote to Mr Patten in January and March last year saying it was having
difficulty complying with the regulations as it had been refused Aito
membership and could not get quotations from insurance companies.
In letters dated January 18 and May 5 Mr Heseltine said the company did not
need to comply with the regulations. 'This is because the customer is
required himself to specify what ferry service he wishes to use, without
advice or assistance from the company selling the holiday.'
Mr Noel Josephides, Aito chairman, said if Mr Heseltine's argument were
accepted, 'most of our members wouldn't require bonding'. He said virtually
every company selling French holidays allowed customers to choose the ferry
crossing they wanted.
Abta said Mr Heseltine's advice would create a 'huge problem' for consumers.
'The DTI has been telling consumers that they're protected, but there's
nobody there to enforce that. We've said all along that it's only a matter
of time before a tour operator collapses and people lose their holidays,' it
said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
