<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Tireless fighter for miners: Obituary: Lord Gormley
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
JOE GORMLEY, president of the National Union of Mineworkers from 1971 to
1982, died yesterday aged 75 after a long illness.
During his stormy years as leader, Lord Gormley led the miners through two
national coal strikes in the early 1970s, taking them back to the top of the
manual wage earnings table after a long period of decline. But he always
rejected the views of his union's vocal left-wing.
He was prepared to fight for his members' interests but had no wish to
confront governments.
A hard-headed pragmatist, Gormley practised the art of negotiating. His
canny bargaining skills were coupled with a sureness of touch in reading the
often uncertain mood of the coalfields.
But Gormley could not always deliver his promises, as Conservative prime
minister Edward Heath learned to his cost in 1973, when he sought a deal to
prevent a miners' strike. Gormley was unable to sell the deal to his
executive, contributing to Heath's downfall in the February 1974 general
election, fought partly on the issue of union power.
Under Gormley the NUM became one of Britain's most powerful unions.
In alliance with Coal Board chairman Sir Derek Ezra he lobbied successfully
for massive investment and subsidies after the quadrupling of oil prices in
1973 seemed to restore coal's lost power as a strategic fuel.
In his later presidential years Gormley found it difficult to contain his
union's resurgent left.
Born in Lancashire, Gormley left school at 14 and spent his next 28 years
down the pit. He was elected to the NUM executive in 1957, and became
north-west area secretary four years later. In 1971 he defeated the Scottish
miners leader Mick McGahey to become NUM president.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
