FT  28 MAY 93 / Ramos may sanction newN-plants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MANILA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Fidel Ramos has ordered energy officials to study the possibility
of building new nuclear plants to help solve a power crisis, Reuter reports
from Manila.
The Philippines has mothballed its first nuclear plant, built by
Westinghouse Electric in 1985, calling it unsafe. The US company has denied
the charge, and a Philippine claim for compensation is pending before an
international arbitration panel in Geneva.
Mr Ramos last night directed Mr Delfin Lazaro, the energy secretary, to
study the feasibility of putting up new nuclear plants, a presidential
palace statement said.
Mr Ramos said he did not oppose setting up nuclear power plants as long as
they were in places where they posed no danger to people, but the 600 MW
Bataan plant built by Westinghouse would probably be operated as a coal- or
oil-fired power project.
Manila and the rest of Luzon island suffer some eight hours of power cuts
daily because of low generating capacity, worsened by the frequent breakdown
of ageing power plants.
