<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / World Trade News: US bans EC from bids on Dollars 20m
contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Clinton administration yesterday imposed a ban on bids by EC companies
for Dollars 20m (Pounds 13m) worth of US government contracts. There has
been a long transatlantic dispute over the Community's utilities procurement
rules. Sir Leon Brittan, the EC's top trade negotiator, said the move was
'neither justified, wise or necessary'. The EC could not ignore the 'wholly
unjustified action.'
The US move was was nevertheless expected.
In April the US and EC resolved part of the dispute over procurement of
heavy electric power equipment by allowing each other's companies to bid on
government contracts without receiving special preferences. But because the
two sides could not agree on telecommunications rules, Mr Mickey Kantor, the
US trade representative, was forced to act to satisfy both Congress and US
law. Mr Kantor originally threatened about Dollars 45m in sanctions just as
a first step. The ultimate Dollars 20m action could be seen as no more than
symbolic.
The US and EC agreed to a process which they expect to lead to an accord in
negotiations on the procurement code of the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade.
