<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Deadlocked Russian cabinet fiddles while the rouble burns:
The currency approach 1,000 to the dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE ornate hall of a Stalinist-era skyscraper, the young men with the
cellular telephones yesterday saw the relentless slide of the rouble as a
reflection of everything that is wrong with the Russian economy.
As the Russian currency teetered on the brink of the psychological threshold
of Rbs1,000 to the dollar - only to be stopped at Rbs994 by the central bank
selling what is thought to have been Dollars 30m dollars for roubles, so
President Boris Yeltsin was telling the cabinet that stabilising the
exchange rate should be one of its key priorities.
Apart from making the politicians jumpy, the currency's slide is seen as a
national humiliation by ordinary Russians brought up on decades of the
artificially-fixed exchange rate where one rouble was worth more than the US
dollar.
'This psychological aspect does not affect dealers and banks as it does
public opinion, those who read the newspapers,' said an official on Moscow's
Inter-bank Currency Exchange (Micex), where the rouble is traded twice a
week. 'Those who are part of the market have a kind of objective view of
what's happening. The round numbers do not make any difference.'
Since the launch of market reforms a year and a half ago, the rouble's
decline against the dollar from Rbs200 has been an unpleasant mirror of high
inflation, lax credit policies, and a lack of faith in politicians' promises
to make things better. Few observers doubt it will go through the Rbs1,000
barrier when trading resumes on Monday, as part of a new pattern of daily
trading.
'It would be very strange if the rouble stabilised since credit emission is
continuing despite all this talk of stabilisation,' said Mr Andrei Koshelev
one of the dealers representing the Russian banks which trade on the
exchange.
'Everybody is looking for a miracle to live better,' said Mr Alexei Osenmuk,
the exchange's deputy director. 'But the rouble reflects the real situation
in the economy.'
In his office on the other side of the Moscow River, Mr Kakha Bendukidze,
one of Russia's wealthiest men, smiles with satisfaction. As the head of a
large private group of companies, he makes most of his money exporting
Russia's rich natural resources for dollars, and is delighted that the
central bank is no longer intervening aggressively to support the currency
as it did last year because this means the currency's fall is uninterrupted
and therefore more predictable.
The slide has, however, caused him to stop importing consumer goods for sale
in Russia. For state importers of commodities such as sugar and grain, which
continue to enjoy subsidised exchange rates, the shock has been less brutal.
But the subsidies indirectly fuel inflation because the central bank simply
prints the money.
For industrial companies which do not enjoy a subsidised exchange rate,
spare parts and inputs are becoming unaffordable or are driving up prices
even further.
Officially, the government and the central bank have agreed that the latter
will no longer sell precious dollars to support the rouble until inflation
is brought under control. Apart from stabilising the country's finances by
cutting the budget deficit, Mr Boris Fyodorov, the finance minister, wants
to widen and deepen the currency market through so-called technical
measures.
These include plans to allow foreign businessmen to open rouble bank
accounts and sell hard currency, a move which has been resisted by the
central bank as enabling foreigners to buy up Russian assets on the cheap.
But many Russian officials agree with western lawyers and bankers in saying
that opening the market will not help unless the Russian authorities define
clearly what foreigners are allowed to do with roubles.
'It is practically impossible for somebody to invest in something without
firm guarantees, and the right to private property,' says Mr Osenmuk.
There is little doubt that the most important obstacle to the rouble's
stabilisation is the authorities' lack of credibility, stemming from their
failure to implement a united, and comprehensive economic reform package.
Not only do the central bank and finance ministry not trust each other, but
the cabinet itself is divided between radical reformers and conservatives.
President Yeltsin has yet to use his victory in the referendum last month to
break the deadlock.
</TEXT>
