<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Constitutional court to rule on abortion law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE difficulties of integrating two different social systems in Germany will
be tested today when the constitutional court decides whether a new abortion
law is binding.
The law, passed by the Bundestag in June 1992, but immediately referred to
the constitutional court by Chancellor Helmut Kohl, is a reminder that women
in the former east Germany had far more rights than their western
counterparts before unification.
Abortion in the eastern states was available free on demand, without medical
consent, up to the 12th week of pregnancy. In west Germany, abortion was
tightly restricted, requiring recommendation by at least three doctors. This
was anchored to the constitution, which states that 'everyone shall have the
right to life and to inviolability of his person.' In the event, many women
either travelled to Holland, or used personal connections in west Germany.
Unification meant a compromise had to be found. After months of debate, a
free vote was held in the Bundestag. The eastern deputies of the ruling
Christian Democratic Union, the Social Democrats and the liberal Free
Democrats voted to liberalise abortion throughout Germany, but with some
restrictions. A woman had the right to an abortion for up to 12 weeks,
provided she accepted counselling.
The outcome was challenged by Chancellor Kohl, concerned about losing
support from the conservative wing of the CDU and particularly its sister
party, the (Catholic) Christian Social Union (CSU) in Bavaria. He
immediately applied for an injunction to the constitutional court.
As a result, united Berlin is still divided. Women in the west are bound by
pre-1989 restrictions, while women in the east have retained their
pre-unification status.
The court now can throw out the law, ask for amendments, or accept it.
</TEXT>
