<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Lamont angry at dismissal as Major reshapes cabinet: Clarke
is promoted to chancellor - PM seeks to revive government's authority
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT left the Treasury last night angry and embittered after Mr
John Major sought to restore the battered authority of his government by
replacing him as chancellor with Mr Kenneth Clarke.
Ending a power struggle which had threatened to paralyse his government, the
prime minister balanced the elevation of the centrist, pro-European Mr
Clarke with the appointment of the rightist, Euro-sceptic Mr Michael Howard
as home secretary. Mr John Redwood was the only new appointment to the
cabinet, taking the post of Welsh secretary.
But a reshuffle which otherwise resembled a game of political musical chairs
was soured by the acrimony surrounding Mr Lamont's departure.
After refusing to accept a demotion to the post of environment secretary, Mr
Lamont gave public vent to his anger by issuing a terse statement in which
he failed conspicuously to pledge his continuing support for Mr Major.
The statement, sent by facsimile to 10 Downing Street, was a deliberately
abrupt reply to a letter from the prime minister in which Mr Major praised
Mr Lamont for the tough decisions he had taken during his 2 1/2 years at the
Treasury.
In an atmosphere reminiscent of the stormy cabinet departures that preceded
Mrs Margaret Thatcher's downfall in 1990, there was speculation at
Westminster that Mr Lamont might now become a champion for Mr Major's
political enemies on the Conservative backbenches.
Mr Lamont is an instinctive Euro-sceptic whose support for the Maastricht
treaty has been grounded in pragmatism rather than enthusiasm. In his
statement, Mr Lamont said he did not intend to make any further comment 'for
several weeks'. He believed that 'the success of the policies I have put in
place will become increasingly clear with the passage of time'. His
departure after a tense 30-minute meeting with Mr Major yesterday morning
followed a bitter behind-the-scenes power struggle in the highest ranks of
the government.
In spite of the other ministerial changes, the former chancellor and the
manager in 1990 of Mr Major's leadership campaign was left in no doubt that
the principal objective was his removal from the Treasury.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, said the prime minister was like 'the
captain of a ship throwing his first mate off the bridge as they head for
the rocks'. Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, said Mr Lamont's
move was 'a sacking dressed up as a reshuffle'.
A Mori poll in today's Times showed Labour leading the Tories by 16 points.
The poll showed Labour at 44 per cent, the Tories at 28 per cent and the
Liberal Democrats at 24 per cent - one of their highest ratings.
Mr Lamont's efforts to remain in office were overcome by the determination
of Sir Norman Fowler, the party chairman, and Mr Richard Ryder, the chief
whip, that he should be replaced.
Some of Mr Lamont's friends suggested last night he might seek to damage the
prime minister by giving his account of the events which led to sterling's
departure last autumn from the European exchange rate mechanism. Mr Lamont,
whose reputation never recovered from the ERM debacle, refused to accept
blame for an economic strategy set in place by Mr Major.
But senior ministers said that Mr Major's decisive action in sacking Mr
Lamont had restored his personal political authority. To have kept him at
the Treasury would have been an admission of political weakness which would
have continued to drain the prime minister's personal authority and left him
vulnerable to a challenge in the autumn.
Mr Clarke, who alongside Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, is the most
confident and powerful politician in the cabinet, is seen by a majority in
the Conservative party as offering Mr Major his strongest chance of
restoring the government's reputation for economic competence.
Although committed to the principle of managed exchange rates, Mr Clarke has
made clear that he will not risk antagonising the Tory Euro-sceptics by
seeking to take sterling back into the ERM in the short to medium term. He
is also expected to underline his commitment to reducing the level of public
borrowing by keeping to the government's public-spending targets and
continuing with the Treasury's review of the welfare state.
The appointment of Mr Howard as home secretary gives him charge of the most
central element in next year's legislative programme - a crackdown on crime
to restore the government's tarnished reputation as a guardian of law and
order.
Mr Major shuffled the portfolios of six cabinet ministers and made 18 other
alterations to those below cabinet rank. Among those moving were Mr John
Gummer, a close ally of the prime minister. He went from agriculture to the
higher-profile Environment Department. Mr David Hunt moved from the Welsh
Office to the Employment Department, replacing Mrs Gillian Shephard, who
became agriculture secretary.
