<HEADLINE>
FT  28 MAY 93 / Wise men warn on budget deficit and inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Industrial and Economic Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRY and the City were bursting with advice yesterday for the new
chancellor to cut spending and keep a lid on inflation.
The reaction to Mr Kenneth Clarke's appointment came as sterling fell
against the D-Mark amid fears that interest rates would be cut.
Professor David Currie, head of economic forecasts at London Business School
and one of the 'seven wise men' advising the Treasury, said Mr Clarke had
got to 'carry further the policy of getting the budget deficit down' and act
decisively on the threat of inflation.
Mr Roger Bootle, chief economist at Midland Bank, said the new chancellor
should 'substantially cut' public spending to pull back the rising
government deficit, expected to be about Pounds 50bn this financial year.
He said greater openness in policymaking was required, in particular to find
out what went wrong last autumn when Britain was forced to leave the
European exchange rate mechanism.
By contrast, Mr Joe Dwyer, chief executive of Wimpey, the construction
company, called for a more expansionary policy. 'Mr Clarke must now deliver
the economic strategy for sound and sustainable growth which we were
promised by the prime minister,' he said.
Fears that Mr Clarke would cut interest rates and further stimulate the
economy contributed to sterling's weakness on the foreign exchange markets.
Shortly after Mr Clarke's appointment was announced on news agencies, the
pound fell 2 3/4 pfennigs against the D-Mark, reaching a low of DM2.4950
before closing in London at DM2.5075. In late New York trading the pound was
at DM2.5046. Against the dollar it rose nearly a cent in London to close at
Dollars 1.555. In New York it closed at Dollars 1.56185. Gilts and shares
ended little changed on the day. Some industrialists lined up with the City
economists in urging the chancellor to be tough on spending. Mr Peter
Morgan, director-general of the Institute of Directors, said: 'The priority
of the chancellor has to be to keep inflation under control.'
Mr Martin Taylor, chairman and chief executive of Courtaulds Textiles, said
public finances needed to be brought under control to avoid a sterling
crisis. 'If this (Mr Clarke's appointment) is the way of securing party
unity behind difficult and painful measures, then it had to be done.'
On environment, Mr Charles Secrett, director of Friends of the Earth, said
the key test was whether the incoming Mr John Gummer could win battles with
the other ministries, particularly transport and the Department of Trade and
Industry. Ms Janet Langson, director of the Water Services Association,
representing the water companies, called for 'clear decisions' over
relations with Ofwat, the industry watchdog.
</TEXT>
